In 1428, the Chancellor censured the Mayor, Alderman and Baillives for wresting certain vendibles from common victuallers to the damage os the public market, the detriment os the students and against due course of conscience. In 1448, a general inquisi- tion os victuals was held before Gilbert Kymer, in his chamber at Durham College‚ at which all the iniquities ol the local tradesmen were laid bare by the college manciples. Bakers made bread, bad both in substance colour and taste, and only gave twelve to the dozen to students, but thirteen to townsmen; brewers made beer that was weak and unfit for human consumpti0n; fishmongers sold fish at twice the proper price, and, moreover‚ kept it lor three or four days after its purchase, and conspired with outsiders to keep up the price.
